Welcome to the=C2=A0141=C2=A0newly Not Boring people=C2=A0who have joined u=
s since last Tuesday! If you haven=E2=80=99t subscribed, join=C2=A0211,865 =
smart, curious folks by subscribing here:
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring is brought to you by=E2=80=A6Mercury [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/3daf2742-0069-4ec0-8fd1-ddcf1e700f85?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Mercury is banking engineered for startups. But they go beyond banking, pro=
viding the resources and connections startups need to become success storie=
s. We=E2=80=99ve used Mercury at Not Boring since day 1=E2=80=A6and frankly=
, it=E2=80=99s very rare I see a startup that doesn=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
As the banking platform of choice for startups, Mercury has a unique perspe=
ctive on the fundraising landscape today. They published those insights in =
this article [ https://substack.com/redirect/3daf2742-0069-4ec0-8fd1-ddcf1e=
700f85?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
 =E2=80=93 highlighting the metrics and milestones investors care most abou=
t today.
The headline is that investors are still looking for opportunities, but hav=
e shifted exactly what they=E2=80=99re looking for. Soif you=E2=80=99re a s=
tartup founder, nail your next investor convo by locking in on what investo=
rs are looking for by reading Mercury=E2=80=99s full free article [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/3daf2742-0069-4ec0-8fd1-ddcf1e700f85?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Mercury is a financial technology company, not a bank. Banking services pro=
vided by Choice Financial Group and Evolve Bank & Trust; Members FDIC.
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=C2=A0
Happy Tuesday! What a weekend. We were at my parents=E2=80=99 celebrating m=
y mom=E2=80=99s birthday this weekend. Our car got stolen out of the drivew=
ay early Sunday morning. The police were great, we tracked the car down wit=
h an app, and we got it back yesterday. There was some damage, but all-in-a=
ll, we got lucky.=C2=A0
That does mean that a lot of the time I would have spent writing was spent =
tracking down the car, so I had to go a little off the dome with this one. =
Last week, I wrote about the idea that capitalism is good and capitalism ca=
n evolve. As Bill Gurley highlighted, one of the best ways to evolve capita=
lism is to fight back against regulatory capture in order to unlock an Age =
of Miracles.=C2=A0This piece digs into that idea. It=E2=80=99s meant to be =
a starting point for a discussion, not to have all the answers.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Gang Captures Washington
The reason Silicon Valley has been so successful is because it=E2=80=99s so=
 fucking far away from Washington, DC.
- Bill Gurley
Last week, Benchmark partner Bill Gurley gave a talk at the All-In Summit [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/9e5d7dd5-fd96-40d3-ad59-bdd426f387ef?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] on regulatory=
 capture.=C2=A0
He wrapped it up with a banger:=C2=A0 =E2=80=9CThe reason Silicon Valley ha=
s been so successful is because it=E2=80=99s so fucking far away from Washi=
ngton, DC.=E2=80=9D
That=E2=80=99s a great line. It brought the house down. Regulatory capture =
sucks.=C2=A0
I was listening to it on a run, and when he said it, I did a very little, i=
nconspicuous fist pump.=C2=A0
But when I thought about it once the endorphins wore off, it seemed more li=
ke the end of a chapter.=C2=A0
Silicon Valley may have been so successful to date because it=E2=80=99s so =
fucking far away from Washington, DC. It=E2=80=99s been the plucky, underes=
timated, unwashed underdog, and when you=E2=80=99re the plucky, underestima=
ted, unwashed underdog, you can use that status to rack up surprise wins.=
=C2=A0
But when you=E2=80=99re the favorite, when you=E2=80=99re expected to win, =
when opponents design strategies to prevent you from winning, the game chan=
ges. You can=E2=80=99t just rack up surprise wins far away from Washington,=
 DC anymore. You need to accept that you have a target on your back, and do=
 everything it takes to win by competing directly.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s where Silicon Valley is today. It=E2=80=99s coming for the b=
ig prizes =E2=80=93 trillion-dollar industries like energy, finance, health=
care, defense, telecommunications, education, manufacturing, automotive, an=
d white-collar work =E2=80=93 and facing savvy incumbents at every turn.=C2=
=A0
We have the opportunity to live in an Age of Miracles. Cheap energy. Abunda=
nt intelligence. Supersonic transportation. Distributed opportunity. Longer=
, healthier lives for billions. To realize that opportunity, though, is goi=
ng to take a lot of messy, bare-knuckled work that Silicon Valley has had t=
he luxury of being unaccustomed to.=C2=A0
If Silicon Valley really wants to make the world a better place, it needs t=
o recognize that it can=E2=80=99t avoid Washington, DC anymore. It has a re=
sponsibility to fight the regulatory capturers on their own turf and win.=
=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s a hard transition. Let me tell you a story about my experien=
ce failing to make it.
Fat Kid Running=C2=A0
I was a fat kid for most of middle school. I say =E2=80=9Cmost of=E2=80=9D =
because occasionally I=E2=80=99d do Weight Watchers or skip lunch for a wee=
k during basketball camp or train for the one cross country race our league=
 hosted each year. In eighth grade, I got skinny and fast and won.=C2=A0
So on the first day of cross country training camp my freshman year at a ne=
w high school, when Coach McAlpin told the returning runners that there was=
 a new kid who might be pretty fast, Packy McCormick, one of the guys who h=
ad been a year ahead of me in middle school said, =E2=80=9CPacky? He=E2=80=
=99s fat.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
I showed up to camp in a not-fat phase, and on that first run on the trails=
 at Haverford College, I hung with the varsity runners. I ran varsity all y=
ear, the only freshman to make the cut. I finished Second Team All Main Lin=
e [ https://substack.com/redirect/802b2c58-df91-441a-a630-d456c337253e?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Over the =
next couple of years, I got faster. I was First Team All-Main Line [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/69557bb3-7c42-4ce1-83b0-f865bb328788?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] my sophomore year, a=
nd finished sixth in the league championship. I beat the juniors and the se=
niors. My junior year, I was the fastest on the team more often than not. I=
 finished third in the Pennsylvania Independent Schools Championship [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/6c76b1b0-5c2e-4d82-9bbb-eb2f480c6fe7?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], surprising even m=
yself, and then won the league 3200 Meter Championship in the spring. Not b=
ad for a fat kid!=C2=A0
Senior year, I was captain and I was feeling good. I was going to win every=
thing.=C2=A0
And then=E2=80=A6 I didn=E2=80=99t. I distinctly remember kicking a batting=
 cage at Fairmount Park after a particularly disappointing race in which I =
lost to a junior on our team. I did OK at States, but I didn=E2=80=99t win,=
 and I didn=E2=80=99t finish third. I think I finished seventh.=C2=A0
This section from a rival school=E2=80=99s geocities site [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/4bef900a-28c7-4d7f-851d-02cbbe4e4243?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] sums up that year well:=C2=A0
Then came the 3200 meter run, starring the top 4 finishers from Cross Count=
ry championships. Packy McCormick from Episcopal was the defending Inter-Ac=
 Champion, and had never lost to a Malvern runner in track in his high scho=
ol career. Junior Brian Duffy, the defending Cross Country champ, took the =
first 1600 easy in 4:55, then surged past Packy on the 6th lap and ran away=
 with the victory from there, clocking a 9:48 for a negative split second 1=
600 in 4:53, and just 6 seconds off the Inter-Ac Championship record of 9:4=
2.
My memory isn=E2=80=99t great, but that race is still seared in there. It w=
as a hot May day. I=E2=80=99d run a 9:42 earlier in the season =E2=80=93 in=
 an invitational with much faster kids, where I wasn=E2=80=99t expected to =
win and the pressure was off =E2=80=93 and if I just did it again, I=E2=80=
=99d set the league record. As soon as the gun went off, though, I knew it =
wasn=E2=80=99t going to be a record day, that I=E2=80=99d have to fight jus=
t to win it again.=C2=A0
Malvern knew that my strength was my endurance =E2=80=93 I could get a lead=
 early and keep it =E2=80=93 and that my weakness was top-end speed =E2=80=
=93 I had no kick =E2=80=93 and designed a strategy to beat me. They had th=
ree strong runners. Two of them boxed me in, bumped me, and slowed me down =
so that the third could outkick me in the final 800. If I tried to break aw=
ay, one of the two sprinted back in front of me, and then slowed down to me=
ss up my pace. It worked. Duffy, a junior, won, and I finished second in th=
e last race of my high school career. It was devastating.=C2=A0
I learned a painful lesson that season: it=E2=80=99s a lot easier being the=
 up-and-coming underdog than it is being the leader with a target on your b=
ack.=C2=A0
Luckily, the stakes were low. It didn=E2=80=99t matter to the world if I ra=
n two miles faster than another kid. The stakes are higher for Silicon Vall=
ey. It needs to win.=C2=A0
To start, it needs to know what it=E2=80=99s up against. And I think Gurley=
 was right: it=E2=80=99s regulatory capture.
Regulatory Capture=C2=A0
Back to Gurley=E2=80=99s talk and regulatory capture.=C2=A0
Regulatory capture occurs when a regulatory agency, created to act in the p=
ublic interest, acts in the interest of incumbents instead. Gurley gives so=
me colorful examples, like COVID tests.=C2=A0
Germany approved 96 different antigen rapid test vendors; in the US, the FD=
A approved three. Tests cost less than $1 in Germany; they cost $12 in the =
US. Unsurprisingly, the person at the FDA responsible for approving antigen=
 test vendors, Timothy Stenzel, had worked for two of the three approved co=
mpanies.=C2=A0
Does that annoy you? Yeah!=C2=A0
Does it make you mad? Hell yeah!=C2=A0
Does it make you mad enough to call your representative, switch your vote, =
protest in Washington, or organize a lobbying group that will show up year =
after year with millions of dollars in campaign donations so that it never =
happens again?! Errrrr=E2=80=A6 uhhhh=E2=80=A6 no.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s the challenge with regulatory capture in a nutshell.=C2=A0
In his talk, Gurley cites the work of George Stigler, the University of Chi=
cago economist who coined the term =E2=80=9Cregulatory capture=E2=80=9D in =
The theory of economic regulation [ https://substack.com/redirect/5d3a1123-=
3a66-4d2d-804e-4bf0cf5b5278?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in 1971. In a 1989 follow-up, Stigler=E2=80=99s colla=
borator Sam Peltzman wrote [ https://substack.com/redirect/5d3a1123-3a66-4d=
2d-804e-4bf0cf5b5278?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that The theory of economic regulation=E2=80=99s main conclu=
sion was:=C2=A0
In any similar political contest between groups of disparate size, the comp=
act organized interest will usually win at the expense of the diffuse group=
=2E
Gurley asked the audience to repeat =E2=80=9Cregulation is the friend of th=
e incumbent=E2=80=9D after him. I=E2=80=99m going to ask you to repeat this=
 one after me. If you=E2=80=99re at your desk, you can whisper, or type it =
out, or tweet it. OK, on the count of three. One, two, three:
=E2=80=9CThe compact organized interest will usually win at the expense of =
the diffuse group.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
This one insight more than any other describes the bottleneck to progress i=
n America. It means that a few loud, angry, well-organized people can make =
things worse for everyone else. We all care about a lot of things a little =
bit, which gives the advantage to people who care about one thing a lot.=C2=
=A0
This has bugged me for a while. I wrote about it in How to Fix a Country in=
 12 Days [ https://substack.com/redirect/b3c36398-7590-4a71-96d5-8f179743f2=
7e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. I =
tweeted about it in August after Illinois announced it was keeping its mora=
torium on new nuclear in place:=C2=A0
When you=E2=80=99re the underdog, you can avoid captured areas, or blame de=
feat on regulatory capture. You can stay so fucking far away from Washingto=
n, DC.=C2=A0
At some point, though, you need to play to win.=C2=A0
Taking the Fight to Washington
There=E2=80=99s an emergent recognition in Silicon Valley that we=E2=80=99r=
e at this turning point, even if they=E2=80=99re not saying it directly. In=
 the past week alone, four of the most-discussed pieces of content in my co=
rner, in addition to Gurley=E2=80=99s talk, were:
Permissionless [ https://substack.com/redirect/dcd1a958-28ef-4748-98c4-8220=
65a9c7fb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ] by Erik Voorhees
EU Mitigating the Risk of Extinction from AI [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/6333a510-f821-4282-b8ce-4eac2bd7947f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
The Tech Tribe Part I [ https://substack.com/redirect/febadc1f-3da0-4225-b3=
ce-74fa73f9fab3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] & Part II [ https://substack.com/redirect/2d30520e-6522-4a83-b253=
-9fc93cc938ff?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] by Balaji on Moment of Zen=C2=A0
Elon Musk [ https://substack.com/redirect/2d30520e-6522-4a83-b253-9fc93cc93=
8ff?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] by=
 Walter Isaacson=C2=A0
One talk about circumventing the regulators altogether, one story about how=
 dangerous it would be to let Europeans regulate AI, one podcast (in two pa=
rts) about how the tech tribe can take back cities, and one book about the =
one person who=E2=80=99s been able to break through multiple captured indus=
tries.=C2=A0
My Spidey Sense is tingling. This conversation is bubbling up all over the =
internet.
The government itself is often portrayed as the enemy in these discussions,=
 but I think that=E2=80=99s a misplaced and futile fight. Washington is an =
algorithm; there are rules, even if they=E2=80=99re sometimes opaque. If Si=
licon Valley wants to bring about the Age of Miracles, it=E2=80=99s going t=
o need to learn those rules and win the game on the field.=C2=A0
I don=E2=80=99t pretend to know exactly how Silicon Valley can beat the inc=
umbents at their own game. I=E2=80=99m already way out of my depth here. Bu=
t I know that a few things will matter whatever the specifics.=C2=A0
Being well-resourced and well-organized matters.=C2=A0
In one of my favorite essays, Choose Good Quests [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/d4f498d0-97d3-4fc4-a3b0-c81e41b9e8c0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Trae Stephens and Markie Wagner write=
 about the moral imperative for founders who=E2=80=99ve gained experience, =
resources, and connections building easier companies early in their careers=
 to use their experience, resources, and connections to tackle really hard,=
 civilizationally important problems in their second act. They call these =
=E2=80=9CGood Quests.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The world is filled with good quests that require massively leveled heroes =
to complete: semiconductor manufacturing, complex industrial automation, na=
tural resource discovery, next-generation energy production, low-cost and l=
ow-labor construction, new modes of transportation, general artificial inte=
lligence, mapping and interfacing with the brain, extending the human lifes=
pan. These future-defining problems are hard to recruit for, difficult to r=
aise money for, and nearly impossible to build near-term businesses around,=
 which is why they are exactly the types of problems we need the most well-=
resourced players pursuing.
Silicon Valley is going through the same arc on the meta-level, accumulatin=
g experience, resources, and connections over the past half century that it=
 must now put towards Good Quests.=C2=A0
This is already underway at the company level =E2=80=93 I can name multiple=
 companies attacking each of the challenges listed in the quote =E2=80=93 b=
ut in order for them to have the greatest odds of success and largest impac=
t, Silicon Valley has to give them air cover on the regulatory front.=C2=A0
Silicon Valley is well-resourced, but it needs to be better organized. Curr=
ently, it faces the same challenge of diffused support that Stigler wrote a=
bout in 1971. =E2=80=9CTech=E2=80=9D is a loose collection of people and co=
mpanies that use technology to try to improve something. They take differen=
t approaches and attack different industries.=C2=A0
While tech calls some of the largest companies in the world =E2=80=93 Apple=
, Amazon, Google, Meta, Nvidia =E2=80=93 its own, each individual company f=
acing an established industry likely faces better-resourced and better-orga=
nized incumbents.=C2=A0
Crypto startups face a regulatory apparatus captured by the financial servi=
ces industry, as evidenced by Elizabeth Warren=E2=80=99s Anti-Crypto Army. =
Nuclear fission startups face a regulatory apparatus captured by oil and ga=
s companies and the environmentalists they back, and fusion is likely to fa=
ce the same. When the All-In hosts asked him about fusion after the talk, G=
urley didn=E2=80=99t seem optimistic.=C2=A0
Silicon Valley now has the resources, and it needs to capture a regulatory =
apparatus of its own, starting with getting clear about what it stands for =
and rallying people around that mission. This is as good a quest for entrep=
reneurs to embark on as any particular technological innovation.=C2=A0
I think the e/acc movement [ https://substack.com/redirect/a9a10ddc-fa55-49=
d3-b7b4-d74a202a51cb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is working in the right direction here. As much of an optimi=
st as I am, I realize that battle lines need to be drawn, and the idea of a=
cceleration versus deceleration or growth versus degrowth is a clarifying o=
ne. It=E2=80=99s as strong a Schelling Point as I=E2=80=99ve seen in tech.
It=E2=80=99s also too jargony to go mainstream. Thermodynamics, AGI, and Ka=
rshdev Scales work to rally the in-group, but to garner the necessary popul=
ar support, the message needs to go mainstream.=C2=A0
Passionate popular support matters.=C2=A0
Silicon Valley needs to both share an optimistic vision of the world it can=
 create with and for people, which it does an OK-but-not-great job on, and =
make people aware of what=E2=80=99s at stake when incumbents block progress=
 out of their own self-interest.=C2=A0
Hope and Anger.
On the anger side, people need to be acutely aware of the fact that regulat=
ory capture is definitionally anti-consumer. When it occurs, a small group =
receives benefits at the expense of the larger population.=C2=A0
The stories that Gurley shared about regulatory capture demonstrate this.=
=C2=A0
More expensive COVID tests mean three companies benefit at the expense of h=
undreds of millions of people paying more. Comcast blocking city-wide WiFi =
means that Comcast benefits at the expense of 1.5 million Philadelphians. E=
pic making healthcare providers use shittier software means that Epic benef=
its at the expense of millions of people who have a harder time dealing wit=
h an already complex healthcare system. All three examples stand in contras=
t to the competition that helps make America great.=C2=A0
These stories should make people angry, and they=E2=80=99re not the worst o=
f them.=C2=A0
Back in June, I did a quick and dirty analysis [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/1ed9f9b9-7c01-4135-b171-849e78c1d378?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] of the number of deaths caused by using =
more dangerous energy sources instead of nuclear, and it=E2=80=99s somethin=
g like 59 million deaths over the past 30 years.=C2=A0
That should make people furious, but that story doesn=E2=80=99t have the sa=
me resonance as images from Chernobyl or Fukushima, which were far, far les=
s deadly.=C2=A0
The fact that tens of thousands of depressed people in the US commit suicid=
e each year when we=E2=80=99ve known of the benefits of psychedelics with t=
alk therapy when treating depression for decades but classified them as Sch=
edule I drugs should make people furious.=C2=A0
Just last night, Roon made a similar point about self-driving cars:=C2=A0
This chart comparing the prices of goods in heavily-regulated versus less-r=
egulated industries should make people furious. It should be plastered acro=
ss cities and towns throughout the country, and even though it=E2=80=99s al=
ready shared often online, it should be shared more.=C2=A0
One of Silicon Valley=E2=80=99s challenges is that counterfactuals are hard=
 to comprehend. It=E2=80=99s difficult to grok what could have been if thin=
gs had gone differently: all of the people who wouldn=E2=80=99t have died i=
f we used more nuclear instead of coal, all the people who would still be a=
live if research into psychedelics had continued, how cheap healthcare and =
education could be if those industries weren=E2=80=99t captured.=C2=A0
Silicon Valley will need to figure out how to spread that message.=C2=A0
And then there=E2=80=99s hope.
At the same time, Silicon Valley needs to do a better job describing what c=
ould still be in ways that demonstrate the real impact on peoples=E2=80=99 =
lives today.=C2=A0
That starts, of course, with building technology that clearly improves peop=
les=E2=80=99 lives. Safer self-driving cars, cheaper energy, cheaper housin=
g, better medicines. Cheaper and better across the board. In the underdog p=
hase, social media and SaaS were valuable stepping stones, but in the leade=
rship phase, Silicon Valley needs to make a clearer positive impact on the =
day-to-day.=C2=A0
Of course, there=E2=80=99s a chicken and egg here. Regulatory capture can m=
ake it hard to actually do the things that Silicon Valley wants to do, so i=
t needs to yell loudly whenever roadblocks are thrown in its way. Gurley=E2=
=80=99s point on the need for increased transparency and communication on r=
egulatory capture is a good one.=C2=A0
The message needs to be clear: if you let us cook, and come cook with us, w=
e will make everything cheaper and increase all of our standards of living.=
 On a podcast recently, someone made the point that billionaires and regula=
r people all use the same iPhone connected to the same internet. That can b=
e true for pretty much everything except land.=C2=A0
People need to be motivated enough to call their representatives, switch th=
eir votes, protest in Washington, or organize lobbying groups that will sho=
w up year after year with millions of dollars in campaign donations so that=
 it never happens again.=C2=A0
Again, I don=E2=80=99t have the answers for how we do this, but Silicon Val=
ley needs to get popular support on its side.
The good news is, while the scams and blowups get the headline, I genuinely=
 believe that Silicon Valley has truth on its side. Its incentives are bett=
er aligned with the general population=E2=80=99s than the incumbents=E2=80=
=99 are. Tech companies win when they=E2=80=99re able to provide better, ch=
eaper things to more people.=C2=A0
Playing the long game matters.
Silicon Valley=E2=80=99s luminaries like Jeff Bezos talk about the importan=
ce of playing the long game. That=E2=80=99s more important in this battle t=
han it is for any particular company.=C2=A0
This war certainly won=E2=80=99t be won overnight. It will take years of st=
rategic organization, clear communication, and most importantly, delivering=
 on promises. When Silicon Valley is successful in defeating regulatory cap=
ture in a certain industry, it needs to show that it actually delivers resu=
lts. Every time it does that, it will gain support for the next, harder bat=
tle.
Techno-capitalism and America, at its best, go hand-in-hand. It=E2=80=99s S=
ilicon Valley=E2=80=99s responsibility not to overthrow the system, but to =
improve it, to get pro-growth candidates elected, work with regulators to h=
elp them do their job by protecting the interests of the American people, a=
nd prove that government and industry can work together for the benefit of =
all.=C2=A0
And if it succeeds in capturing Washington, it will need to do the hardest =
imaginable thing: use that capture for the good of innovation and the good =
of the people. It will need to somehow open source regulatory capture and o=
pen itself up to disruption from the next up-and-coming underdog.=C2=A0
The fact that leading tech companies already try to use regulatory capture =
for their own benefit demonstrates how difficult this challenge will be, bu=
t it=E2=80=99s crucially important.
If Silicon Valley=E2=80=99s mission really is to make the world a better pl=
ace, it must recognize its responsibility to lead, fight on behalf of the p=
eople against incumbents, and do what it takes to win. Then it will have ea=
rned the right to show what=E2=80=99s possible.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s the game on the field: capture Washington back and change it=
 for the better.
In the coming decades, Silicon Valley will need to be successful by getting=
 so fucking close to Washington, DC that it can improve it from the inside.
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/bca40df1-877f-4574-bd39-6f7da=
ee5f036?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for editing!
That=E2=80=99s all for today! We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 with the Weekly Dose.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

